MAMware: whats your opinion on this Error Handling Improvements

Problem: Some async operations lack proper error boundaries
```
// In processFrame - should wrap in try-catch
const result = await processFrame(DOM, video.videoWidth, video.videoHeight);
```

GitHub Copilot: Here’s a quick improvement you can make around that `processFrame` call:

````javascript
try {
    const result = await processFrame(DOM, video.videoWidth, video.videoHeight);
    // …use result…
} catch (err) {
    console.error('processFrame failed:', err);
    // optionally: show a fallback UI, increment an error metric, or skip this frame
}
````

You might also extract a small helper if you have many of these:

````javascript
async function withErrorBoundary(fn, ...args) {
  try {
    return { data: await fn(...args), error: null };
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(fn.name, 'error:', error);
    return { data: null, error };
  }
}

// usage
const { data, error } = await withErrorBoundary(processFrame, DOM, video.videoWidth, video.videoHeight);
if (error) { /* fallback */ }
````

This pattern ensures every async operation gets its own boundary and standardized logging/fallback logic.

